    <item>
      <title>Whitespace</title>
      <link>https://vishvAsa.github.io/sanskrit/lekhanam/whitespace/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://vishvAsa.github.io/sanskrit/lekhanam/whitespace/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;उचचरणन-समबनध&#34;&gt;उच्चारणेन सम्बन्धः&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;प्रायः&lt;/strong&gt; सर्वत्र वस्तुतो वाक्यानां लेखने रिक्तस्थानेषु दर्शितेष्व् अपि,&lt;br&gt;&#xA;उच्चारणे तत्कारणाद् विरामो न लक्ष्यते।&lt;br&gt;&#xA;उदाहरणाय, गतवाक्यम् उक्त्वा पश्यतु, साधारण-रीत्या।&lt;br&gt;&#xA;केवलम्, &amp;lsquo;।॥&amp;rsquo; इति चिह्नेन &amp;lsquo;,&amp;rsquo; चिह्नेन च सूचितयोस् स्थानयोश् च विरामो ऽनुभूयते।&lt;br&gt;&#xA;स्वर-व्यत्ययस् तु यथा साधारणं भिन्नपदेषु दृश्यते -&lt;br&gt;&#xA;तत्र न किमप्य् उच्यते।&lt;br&gt;&#xA;कदाचित् तदृश-छिह्नाभावेऽपि विरामो लक्ष्येत, परन्तु &amp;ldquo;तद् रिक्तस्थानस्य कारणाद् एव&amp;rdquo; इति न वक्तुम् अर्हामः। प्रायः तत्र विरामचिह्नयोजनं श्रेयस इति वचनन्तु साधु स्यात्।&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;आङ्ग्लिके ऽपि तथैव। &amp;ldquo;I went to hear the conference call. But it was so noisy that I quit.&amp;rdquo; इति वाक्यं सस्वरं यथासाधारणम् उक्त्वा परीक्षताम्। तत्रापि न कुत्रापि विरामो लक्ष्यते। एवं &amp;ldquo;रिक्तस्थानात् पृथक्पठनं&amp;rdquo; नाम विरामस्वीकृतिर् इति सूचिता चेत् तर्हि, &amp;ldquo;हरिर् आगतः&amp;rdquo; इत्यादौ पृथक्पठनस्य संभावना एव नास्ति।&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>इतिहासः</title>
      <link>https://vishvAsa.github.io/sanskrit/lekhanam/itihAsaH/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://vishvAsa.github.io/sanskrit/lekhanam/itihAsaH/</guid>
      <description>&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;‘तद् यथा शङ्कुना सर्वाणि पर्णानि सन्तृण्णान्य्+++(=संविद्धानि)+++ एवम् ओङ्कारेण सर्वा वाक् सन्तृण्णा। ओङ्कार एवेदं सर्वम्।’ (छा.उ. २। २३। ३) पर्ण-ग्रन्थस्योल्लेखो ऽयम् इति केचित्।&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;early-inadequacy&#34;&gt;Early inadequacy&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;All indications are that the spoken language for which the early scripts (brahmi &amp;amp; kharosthi) were invented did not follow a fully scientific (or standardized) mapping of sounds to script, so the early scripts did not allow for phonetically accurate representation of the spoken language.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&amp;ldquo;In fact the kharosthi script in its early centuries did not even show vowel length distinctions but this is no evidence to show that the underlying spoken Indo-Aryan language in the 4th century BCE had shed its all its long vowels. It is only an evidence that the script did not allow such vowel length distinctions to be orthographically represented (until that script evolved enough over the centuries to allow fully phonetic representation of the spoken language &amp;ndash; and voila, you have phonetically accurate sanskrit appearing after centuries of apparent written &amp;ldquo;prakrit&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; when really all that had happened is only that the script had evolved, not so much the spoken language).&amp;rdquo; &lt;a href=&#34;https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/bvparishat/e26Gh14ohxI&#34;&gt;रामकृष्णः&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
